commentBody:
@NobodyThree 
I didn't see anything wrong with it.

OM NOM NOM has been in use for years, as the sound you make when you eat something. It's a fairly common onomatopoeia -- or OM NOM NOM-topoeia, if you will.

@Lorne Eckersley 

I'd be willing to bet that most folks who participate in the Wordplay comments section hate what's going on in America at the moment just as much as you, if not more so, whether American or otherwise. What's that got to do with the puzzle or the constructor? 

Just because you didn't enjoy the puzzle doesn't mean it's objectively bad or that you can somehow read the constructor's mind. You're just showing your own small-mindedness. We've already got enough of that in Washington.

@Striker 
My son was about 11 then and a huge A's fan. I'll never forget that crestfallen look on his face when (Dennis) Eckersley served that fat one to Gibson. 
And you know, if Gibson had only hit a triple instead of a homer, he'd have been thrown out at first base. I knew in that moment that the A's would go on to lose the series.

@Cal Gal 

Yes!  That look on Eckersley's face was priceless.

I was a very big anti-fan of the Dodgers, so I probably had the same look on my face.

@Lorne Eckersley 
I couldn't disagree with you more about this puzzle, and I'm in the same bad mood as you are. 

Of course, I don't blame the people of the US (or at least not the slight majority).

@Mike 
This pun has met with some resistance.

If you liked it, though, more power to you.

@Mrs Jones 

Thank you! 

I didn't know it and totally forgot to look it up post-solve, so I appreciate your clarification.

@Andrzej 

I am hopeless with the geography of the Balkan states.  When I was in elementary school, it was known as Yugoslavia, and everyone was saying that the country would only last as long as Tito lasted.

Sure enough, when it came apart, I was was well past school, and I never internalized the new map.

@Francis 

I visited the country as a child when it was still Yugoslavia ("Southern Slavs [Land]", literally). A few years later war broke out, and it was on the news for much of the 90s. Bosnia, Herzegovina, Croatia, Serbia - those names came up so often there was no way I would not remember them. Then in 1998/1999 there was the Kosovo war.

Also, these days Croatia is one of Europe's favorite vacation spots. Strangely, since 1988 I visited the region only twice: my family drove through Serbia on our way to Greece in 1998, but we only stopped for lunch there, and then in 2018 when my wife and I were in the Austrian Alps and it rained like crazy, we drove for a day trip to sunny Piran in Slovenia. That's it 😮

@JohnWM 
I've done lots of camping with Cub Scouts and we always called it a groundsheet. 
I think of a tarpaulin as something that covers a load on a huge lorry.

@Bruce 
"purely because I thought it sounded like a plausible name for a giant robot"

You'd be surprised how often this works. "That sounds like a name for X!" is one of my top crossword-solving strategies.

@Lewis - After a few tours with the group, I accidentally learned about an age-old secret tradition called “breezing,” which was that the entire group went without undergarments on the last concert of a tour.

Thankfully, the LMU in Munich was not the last concert of that tour!

(I learned the secret of breezing on a tour that ended in Pittsburgh, where several feet of snow fell as we pulled into town for the concert…❄️

@Lewis 

SNEERS the first answer I got (reliable sources tell me that I am well-practiced, perhaps too much so, at that expression).

Too bad I put it in the grid at 15A, where SNORTS belonged. (I forget Deb Amlen’s term for that phenomenon.)

@Theodore 
I think there were more/longer clues or something, but the ULTRA-TINY print was a serious disservice.  I had to follow DHubby to the shop where his run-about will get some repairs, so my blurred vision had cleared quite a bit, but it was still illegiible.  
There had to be some middle ground--or at least a warning and suggestion for a work-around.

@John Carson - It depends on your interface. If you have anywhere available a ratio dialog, click on it.
On iPhone it is the aA button on upper right. Either way, it means “translation proportionally.”

The thing is - if you make it the opposite of what you think it means (smallen it) - it may well make it do what you want (largen it). Try it, you may well like it.

@jennie 
Were you talking to someone else?  
This note of yours does not relate to my post at all.

@Barry Ancona 

*drops trou to check*
Sir.

